00:00:21.029 --> 00:00:23.570
DENNIS FREEMAN: With that, what
I want to do is think about--

00:00:23.570 --> 00:00:25.370
finish up thinking
about modulation.

00:00:25.370 --> 00:00:27.620
Last time we thought
about modulation

00:00:27.620 --> 00:00:30.410
in a communications context.

00:00:30.410 --> 00:00:31.840
That's a very important context.

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:37.310
It's a way of thinking about how
we can use modulation to better

00:00:37.310 --> 00:00:41.000
match a signal to the medium.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:43.370
So we saw in
particular that if we

00:00:43.370 --> 00:00:46.880
were trying to
transmit human voice

00:00:46.880 --> 00:00:50.540
via electromagnetic
waves, trying to simply

00:00:50.540 --> 00:00:54.770
launch an electrical
representation of the voice

00:00:54.770 --> 00:00:57.957
into electromagnetic waves,
just doesn't work very well.

00:00:57.957 --> 00:01:00.290
And that's because of the
enormous frequency difference.

00:01:00.290 --> 00:01:02.164
We would rather have
frequencies on the order

00:01:02.164 --> 00:01:07.130
of 2 gigahertz for
efficient transmission

00:01:07.130 --> 00:01:12.500
through the atmosphere and
human voices just are not

00:01:12.500 --> 00:01:14.840
centered on 2 gigahertz.

00:01:14.840 --> 00:01:17.930
We can use modulation
to bridge that gap.

00:01:17.930 --> 00:01:21.770
Having done that, we get a
number of other advantages too.

00:01:21.770 --> 00:01:24.770
So for example, we
talked last time

00:01:24.770 --> 00:01:26.790
about the idea of
broadcast radio, which

00:01:26.790 --> 00:01:28.970
was an enormous revolution.

00:01:28.970 --> 00:01:31.730
The idea of being able
to instantly communicate

00:01:31.730 --> 00:01:36.020
lots of stuff like a
newspaper, but instantaneously,

00:01:36.020 --> 00:01:40.040
not with a day or a week
delay, was an enormous deal.

00:01:42.680 --> 00:01:44.620
Today what I want
to think about--

00:01:44.620 --> 00:01:46.730
I mean the way we motivated
last time-- the way

00:01:46.730 --> 00:01:48.729
to do the modulation that
we motivated last time

00:01:48.729 --> 00:01:51.530
was the idea of
amplitude modulation.

00:01:51.530 --> 00:01:54.980
Amplitude modulation is a
terribly non-linear process.

00:01:54.980 --> 00:01:56.750
We multiply two signals.

00:01:56.750 --> 00:02:00.620
That's pretty non-linear.

00:02:00.620 --> 00:02:03.350
And you could
imagine that if we're

00:02:03.350 --> 00:02:06.460
willing to open up
that can of worms

00:02:06.460 --> 00:02:09.650
so that we're willing to
do a transformation that

00:02:09.650 --> 00:02:13.340
is non-linear, there's
enormous numbers of them.

00:02:13.340 --> 00:02:16.010
So you don't have to just
do amplitude modulation.

00:02:16.010 --> 00:02:17.420
You could also do--

00:02:17.420 --> 00:02:18.890
here are three
classics-- you can

00:02:18.890 --> 00:02:22.080
do phase modulation and
frequency modulation as well.

00:02:22.080 --> 00:02:24.080
All of those systems work.

00:02:24.080 --> 00:02:25.970
Phase modulation, the idea is--

00:02:25.970 --> 00:02:27.640
Well, first off,
amplitude modulation.

00:02:27.640 --> 00:02:31.590
The idea was you modulate
so-- this is the carrier.

00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:33.140
cos omega ct is the carrier.

00:02:33.140 --> 00:02:36.470
That's the thing that goes
through the medium well.

00:02:36.470 --> 00:02:39.860
Now we want to somehow embed
the message on the carrier.

00:02:39.860 --> 00:02:43.030
In AM, we did that
by multiplying.

00:02:43.030 --> 00:02:46.600
We take the signal x of
t and we multiply it.

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:48.410
We take the signal
of interest, x of t,

00:02:48.410 --> 00:02:52.100
and we multiply it by the
carrier and transmit that.

00:02:52.100 --> 00:02:55.610
And we saw that, for reasons
of decoding simplicity,

00:02:55.610 --> 00:02:59.060
it was convenient to add
a constant term, which

00:02:59.060 --> 00:03:02.510
was essentially sending, not
only the modulated carrier,

00:03:02.510 --> 00:03:06.380
but also the carrier alone,
so that you could locally

00:03:06.380 --> 00:03:10.970
retrieve both the modulated
message and the carrier.

00:03:10.970 --> 00:03:13.480
It simplified the modulation.

00:03:13.480 --> 00:03:15.500
But a different
kind of alternative

00:03:15.500 --> 00:03:18.190
is, convey the
message in the phase.

00:03:18.190 --> 00:03:18.690
Right?

00:03:18.690 --> 00:03:20.870
We all love phase, right?

00:03:20.870 --> 00:03:21.860
Nod your head yes.

00:03:21.860 --> 00:03:23.960
We all love phase.

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:27.710
So what we could do
instead is take the carrier

00:03:27.710 --> 00:03:32.400
and add a phase term in
proportion to the message.

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:38.370
That's a different way of
coding the message on a carrier.

00:03:38.370 --> 00:03:42.130
Another way to do it is
to code the frequency.

00:03:42.130 --> 00:03:46.290
So take the message,
integrate it--

00:03:46.290 --> 00:03:49.170
it is kind of a funny
way to talk about FM.

00:03:49.170 --> 00:03:52.080
So you could use the
message to modulate

00:03:52.080 --> 00:03:53.940
the frequency of
the carrier, which

00:03:53.940 --> 00:03:55.770
would be very similar
to using the message

00:03:55.770 --> 00:03:57.210
to modulate the phase.

00:03:57.210 --> 00:04:01.570
They, in fact, differ
by an integral.

00:04:01.570 --> 00:04:03.970
And I'll talk about
that more in a minute.

00:04:03.970 --> 00:04:08.730
So the idea then is even though
the first thing they tried--

00:04:08.730 --> 00:04:11.490
the first successful way
of making broadcast radio

00:04:11.490 --> 00:04:14.010
--was via AM, we should
think about the alternatives

00:04:14.010 --> 00:04:15.990
and try to figure out
what are the advantages

00:04:15.990 --> 00:04:20.730
and disadvantages of different
kinds of coding schemes.

00:04:20.730 --> 00:04:24.229
And also consistent with
the goals of this course,

00:04:24.229 --> 00:04:25.770
in thinking about
these alternatives,

00:04:25.770 --> 00:04:27.269
we're going to get
a lot of practice

00:04:27.269 --> 00:04:29.220
in thinking about
Fourier transforms.

00:04:29.220 --> 00:04:30.580
Which is good.

00:04:30.580 --> 00:04:34.770
So let's think about what would
be the difference between AM

00:04:34.770 --> 00:04:38.280
modulation, where we convey
the message by modulating

00:04:38.280 --> 00:04:41.190
the amplitude of the
carrier versus FM,

00:04:41.190 --> 00:04:45.510
where we convey the
message by modulating

00:04:45.510 --> 00:04:49.365
the instantaneous
frequency of the carrier.

00:04:49.365 --> 00:04:51.490
And if we're just looking
at time domain, which is,

00:04:51.490 --> 00:04:53.864
after all, probably the first
place anybody should look--

00:04:53.864 --> 00:04:57.230
if we just compare those two
schemes in the time domain,

00:04:57.230 --> 00:05:00.100
there's some very
big differences.

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:04.060
You can see that when
we amplitude modulate,

00:05:04.060 --> 00:05:08.850
the power that is used
to transmit the message

00:05:08.850 --> 00:05:11.730
depends on the message.

00:05:11.730 --> 00:05:15.060
So there are places where
there is not much power.

00:05:15.060 --> 00:05:17.820
There's not much
energy in this signal.

00:05:17.820 --> 00:05:20.100
And there are places
where there's lots.

00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:22.350
By contrast, down
here you see something

00:05:22.350 --> 00:05:24.090
that has constant power.

00:05:24.090 --> 00:05:25.920
At least if you integrate over--

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:31.010
say you've got a 2
gigahertz carrier,

00:05:31.010 --> 00:05:34.670
then as long as you integrate
over 10 or 20 cycles, which

00:05:34.670 --> 00:05:37.280
is a small fraction
of a second, you're

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:38.990
going to get the same
answer, regardless

00:05:38.990 --> 00:05:42.860
of where in the message
you do the integral.

00:05:42.860 --> 00:05:45.110
So there is obviously
a power difference.

00:05:45.110 --> 00:05:49.460
There's no need to transmit
the carrier in order

00:05:49.460 --> 00:05:52.040
to decode the FM signal,
unless of course you're

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:55.010
interested in understanding
exactly where DC is.

00:05:55.010 --> 00:05:56.570
The interesting
thing about audio

00:05:56.570 --> 00:05:59.900
is that we're very
insensitive to DC.

00:05:59.900 --> 00:06:03.140
So that's not really very
important for conveying

00:06:03.140 --> 00:06:05.720
speech sounds.

00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:08.510
But the original
motivation for thinking

00:06:08.510 --> 00:06:13.830
about alternative ways of
coding was in fact bandwidth.

00:06:13.830 --> 00:06:19.190
So the idea was there's
a limited resource.

00:06:19.190 --> 00:06:21.440
Bandwidth is a limited resource.

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:26.850
If person A is using 1 megahertz
plus or minus 5 kilohertz,

00:06:26.850 --> 00:06:30.680
which is one of the
broadcast AM frequency bands,

00:06:30.680 --> 00:06:32.435
then person B can't
use that band.

00:06:35.120 --> 00:06:37.040
You can have only
one transmitter

00:06:37.040 --> 00:06:39.620
for each of the radio bands.

00:06:39.620 --> 00:06:43.190
That makes bandwidth-- radio
bandwidth --a resource.

00:06:43.190 --> 00:06:46.160
Now there's lots of it.

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:49.880
There's lots of frequencies
between a megahertz and 2

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:51.650
gigahertz.

00:06:51.650 --> 00:06:55.640
On the other hand, there's
lots of people who want it.

00:06:55.640 --> 00:06:57.287
So your local fire
department thinks

00:06:57.287 --> 00:06:59.120
they ought to be able
to talk to each other.

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:00.579
Your local police
department thinks

00:07:00.579 --> 00:07:02.411
they ought to be able
to talk to each other.

00:07:02.411 --> 00:07:03.887
Your local ambulance
service thinks

00:07:03.887 --> 00:07:05.720
they ought to be able
to talk to each other.

00:07:05.720 --> 00:07:08.060
So there's lots of people
with demands for it.

00:07:08.060 --> 00:07:10.100
So the idea of--

00:07:10.100 --> 00:07:13.640
the original pursuit
of FM was to try

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:17.390
to think about a scheme that
would use less bandwidth.

00:07:17.390 --> 00:07:20.990
If you're thinking about speech,
you need about 3 kilohertz.

00:07:20.990 --> 00:07:25.220
3 kilohertz is considered
telephone quality speech.

00:07:25.220 --> 00:07:27.530
It's not perfect,
but it's good enough

00:07:27.530 --> 00:07:31.850
to get very good speech
intelligibility across it.

00:07:31.850 --> 00:07:35.120
So I AM used plus or minus
5 kilohertz bandwidth.

00:07:35.120 --> 00:07:40.190
They allocated a band of 10
kilohertz for every station.

00:07:40.190 --> 00:07:46.530
The initial idea in FM to--
so take this expression for FM

00:07:46.530 --> 00:07:50.240
and think about an
instantaneous frequency omega

00:07:50.240 --> 00:07:55.770
i, which is a frequency with
a slightly different value

00:07:55.770 --> 00:07:57.210
from the carrier frequency.

00:07:57.210 --> 00:08:00.180
It's different because
we're doing FM.

00:08:00.180 --> 00:08:03.570
And you can calculate the
instantaneous frequency

00:08:03.570 --> 00:08:07.550
as the derivative of phase.

00:08:07.550 --> 00:08:12.180
So the derivative of phase gives
you an omega c term out front.

00:08:12.180 --> 00:08:14.577
Omega ct is the carrier phase.

00:08:14.577 --> 00:08:16.160
And then there's the
part of the phase

00:08:16.160 --> 00:08:17.960
that comes from the message.

00:08:17.960 --> 00:08:19.540
So the total
instantaneous frequency

00:08:19.540 --> 00:08:23.120
is omega c plus the time
derivative of phase.

00:08:23.120 --> 00:08:25.570
And since we're
modulating frequency--

00:08:25.570 --> 00:08:28.520
since we're modulating with
the frequency, that turns out

00:08:28.520 --> 00:08:30.920
to be proportional to x.

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:32.990
So the instantaneous
frequency, like you

00:08:32.990 --> 00:08:35.659
would like for frequency
modulation-- the instantaneous

00:08:35.659 --> 00:08:40.580
frequency --is a linear
function of the message x.

00:08:40.580 --> 00:08:43.490
But it's proportional.

00:08:43.490 --> 00:08:49.130
So the reasoning
was make k small.

00:08:49.130 --> 00:08:52.610
If the instantaneous deviations
of frequency are small,

00:08:52.610 --> 00:08:56.830
say 10 to the minus 6th hertz--

00:08:56.830 --> 00:08:58.150
really small.

00:08:58.150 --> 00:09:01.660
Well, if you could have
10 to the minus 6th hertz,

00:09:01.660 --> 00:09:08.670
you could pack 10 to the
6th stations in a hertz.

00:09:08.670 --> 00:09:10.050
Well that's pretty good.

00:09:10.050 --> 00:09:12.810
So instead of using 10
kilohertz to send one message,

00:09:12.810 --> 00:09:14.910
you could get 10
to the 6th messages

00:09:14.910 --> 00:09:16.690
in one hertz of bandwidth.

00:09:16.690 --> 00:09:18.180
That was the
original motivation.

00:09:18.180 --> 00:09:24.300
That was an idea that was
propagated at Bell Labs, who

00:09:24.300 --> 00:09:27.120
were one of the commercial
entities who were seriously

00:09:27.120 --> 00:09:30.570
interested in trying to make
money on broadcast radio.

00:09:30.570 --> 00:09:36.450
So the idea was maybe we could
use FM to squeeze more signals

00:09:36.450 --> 00:09:40.430
in the available bandwidth.

00:09:40.430 --> 00:09:45.210
Well that turns out to
be completely wrong.

00:09:45.210 --> 00:09:47.340
And that's why studying
Fourier transforms

00:09:47.340 --> 00:09:50.370
is such a good example of how
you can use Fourier transforms

00:09:50.370 --> 00:09:52.350
to figure things out.

00:09:52.350 --> 00:09:55.050
That argument is just
completely wrong,

00:09:55.050 --> 00:09:58.260
as two lines of double-0
3 will show you.

00:09:58.260 --> 00:10:02.250
So here is our expression
for the FM signal.

00:10:04.900 --> 00:10:07.120
You can see that it's
complicated because it's

00:10:07.120 --> 00:10:09.240
the cosine of a sum.

00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:11.220
But we all know
from trigonometry,

00:10:11.220 --> 00:10:17.630
the cos of a plus b is cos
a cos b minus sine a sine b.

00:10:17.630 --> 00:10:23.300
So we can get an exact
expression for this part--

00:10:23.300 --> 00:10:25.660
we can expand this
exactly as the cosine

00:10:25.660 --> 00:10:33.830
a times the cosine of b minus
the sine of a times the sign

00:10:33.830 --> 00:10:35.912
of b.

00:10:35.912 --> 00:10:36.620
Well that's easy.

00:10:36.620 --> 00:10:38.750
Now what would happen
to that expression

00:10:38.750 --> 00:10:41.490
if we made k very small?

00:10:41.490 --> 00:10:44.090
Well if we make k very small--

00:10:44.090 --> 00:10:47.150
if k goes close
to 0 --the cosine

00:10:47.150 --> 00:10:50.430
gets arbitrarily close to 1.

00:10:50.430 --> 00:10:54.060
Fine, that sounds OK.

00:10:54.060 --> 00:10:59.210
This sine of l times something
does not go-- well the fallacy

00:10:59.210 --> 00:11:02.370
in the reasoning
was that goes to 0.

00:11:02.370 --> 00:11:06.120
It does go to 0, but it
actually goes to 0 slowly.

00:11:06.120 --> 00:11:09.400
It actually-- the limit
approaches k times--

00:11:09.400 --> 00:11:14.340
so the limit of the sine of
theta, as theta gets small,

00:11:14.340 --> 00:11:14.940
is theta.

00:11:17.890 --> 00:11:21.300
So the idea wasn't quite right.

00:11:21.300 --> 00:11:23.610
It doesn't go
arbitrarily close to 0.

00:11:23.610 --> 00:11:28.780
It gets arbitrarily
close to the message.

00:11:28.780 --> 00:11:31.480
So that means that
this expression, which

00:11:31.480 --> 00:11:38.380
looks horrible up here, is
equivalent to this expression,

00:11:38.380 --> 00:11:41.280
which says that the signal
that I'm transmitting

00:11:41.280 --> 00:11:43.320
is the carrier.

00:11:43.320 --> 00:11:54.310
Just like AM minus sine
omega ct times the message.

00:11:54.310 --> 00:11:56.076
But that's just AM.

00:11:56.076 --> 00:11:57.610
I took the message times sine.

00:11:57.610 --> 00:11:58.290
Uh, it's sine.

00:11:58.290 --> 00:12:00.329
It's not cosine, who cares?

00:12:00.329 --> 00:12:02.120
That's a difference of
90 degrees of phase.

00:12:02.120 --> 00:12:03.500
Who cares?

00:12:03.500 --> 00:12:05.610
It's AM.

00:12:05.610 --> 00:12:09.730
The fallacy in the
reasoning is that this k

00:12:09.730 --> 00:12:12.750
does not-- the sine of
theta, when theta gets small,

00:12:12.750 --> 00:12:13.860
does not go to 0.

00:12:13.860 --> 00:12:15.970
It goes to theta.

00:12:15.970 --> 00:12:19.530
And so the limiting
case for narrowband FM

00:12:19.530 --> 00:12:24.460
has precisely the
same bandwidth as AM.

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:27.060
Narrowband FM has the
same bandwidth as AM,

00:12:27.060 --> 00:12:28.920
so therefore, this
whole idea that you

00:12:28.920 --> 00:12:33.810
could use FM to squeeze more
channels into a given bandwidth

00:12:33.810 --> 00:12:36.696
is just completely wrong.

00:12:36.696 --> 00:12:38.070
So it was the
initial motivation.

00:12:38.070 --> 00:12:40.380
It's just wrong.

00:12:40.380 --> 00:12:46.432
In fact, what's good about
FM is the other limit.

00:12:46.432 --> 00:12:47.640
Don't worry about narrowband.

00:12:47.640 --> 00:12:50.070
Worry about broadband.

00:12:50.070 --> 00:12:51.360
The value of FM--

00:12:51.360 --> 00:12:53.040
and this was Armstrong again.

00:12:53.040 --> 00:12:56.580
The same guy who did the
superheterodyne receiver, which

00:12:56.580 --> 00:12:59.520
made AM broadcast
radio possible.

00:12:59.520 --> 00:13:02.850
Same guy went on
to think about FM

00:13:02.850 --> 00:13:05.670
and he saw that the
value of FM was, in fact,

00:13:05.670 --> 00:13:07.800
to use lots of bandwidth.

00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:09.084
Why would you do that?

00:13:09.084 --> 00:13:10.250
Well, we'll see in a minute.

00:13:10.250 --> 00:13:12.390
That the reason you want
to use a lot of bandwidth

00:13:12.390 --> 00:13:17.070
is that you generate a robust
signal that can be recovered,

00:13:17.070 --> 00:13:19.500
even when noise
gets added to it.

00:13:19.500 --> 00:13:21.210
One of the big
problems, especially

00:13:21.210 --> 00:13:24.411
with the early versions
of AM broadcast radio,

00:13:24.411 --> 00:13:26.410
was that it had a lot of
noise in the background

00:13:26.410 --> 00:13:28.620
we called static.

00:13:28.620 --> 00:13:31.650
Kind of like tsss, but
a little bit more poppy

00:13:31.650 --> 00:13:34.230
and more irritating.

00:13:34.230 --> 00:13:37.620
And Armstrong figured
out that there was a way

00:13:37.620 --> 00:13:42.390
to reduce that static by
using more bandwidth to make

00:13:42.390 --> 00:13:43.750
a more robust signal.

00:13:43.750 --> 00:13:44.910
So that's the idea.

00:13:44.910 --> 00:13:48.930
And coincidentally, it gives
us an excellent opportunity

00:13:48.930 --> 00:13:50.520
to practice our
skills of figuring out

00:13:50.520 --> 00:13:52.110
Fourier transforms.

00:13:52.110 --> 00:13:56.170
So let's figure out the Fourier
transform of an FM signal.

00:13:56.170 --> 00:13:56.670
Right?

00:13:56.670 --> 00:13:59.040
That'll be fun.

00:13:59.040 --> 00:14:01.260
Remember what the FM
signal looked like?

00:14:01.260 --> 00:14:05.260
We saw back here, it's
kind of horrendous looking.

