00:30:58.830 --> 00:31:00.790
What should I do next?

00:31:00.790 --> 00:31:01.505
Demodulate it.

00:31:01.505 --> 00:31:02.380
So how do we do that?

00:31:08.380 --> 00:31:10.000
Do the same process when--

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:13.220
and that process was?

00:31:13.220 --> 00:31:15.480
So I put stripes--

00:31:15.480 --> 00:31:17.270
I illuminated the
picture with stripes

00:31:17.270 --> 00:31:19.400
in order to make the original.

00:31:19.400 --> 00:31:26.350
Now what I should do is
illuminate the result

00:31:26.350 --> 00:31:27.000
with stripes.

00:31:31.260 --> 00:31:33.820
If I multiply the
picture by stripes

00:31:33.820 --> 00:31:37.780
I'm phase modulating it.

00:31:37.780 --> 00:31:41.050
Multiply by cos omega
whatever, right?

00:31:41.050 --> 00:31:43.090
So now I'll put
the clicker down.

00:31:43.090 --> 00:31:44.170
No cheating, right?

00:31:44.170 --> 00:31:46.600
Nothing up my sleeves.

00:31:46.600 --> 00:31:49.030
And now I'm going to project
that stripey pattern.

00:31:55.580 --> 00:31:56.402
Cute, huh?

00:32:00.560 --> 00:32:01.430
It's pretty amazing.

00:32:04.320 --> 00:32:06.310
So who is that?

00:32:06.310 --> 00:32:06.990
Fourier.

00:32:06.990 --> 00:32:07.489
Good.

00:32:11.160 --> 00:32:15.870
That's the principle behind
Michael's microscope.

00:32:15.870 --> 00:32:19.320
And by the way,
I'm not cheating.

00:32:19.320 --> 00:32:20.355
So if I roll the phase--

00:32:26.210 --> 00:32:28.750
It works just like radio.

00:32:33.900 --> 00:32:35.370
Now how's it work?

00:32:35.370 --> 00:32:37.035
And how well-- so
that was a demo.

00:32:40.680 --> 00:32:42.120
Stan's committee loved it.

00:32:47.580 --> 00:32:48.880
Here's the idea.

00:32:48.880 --> 00:32:52.260
So the poster was phase
modulated Fourier.

00:32:52.260 --> 00:32:56.490
Fourier is a
function of x and y.

00:32:56.490 --> 00:32:58.735
And you modulate the
phase of carrier.

00:32:58.735 --> 00:33:01.530
The carrier now is
the y displacement

00:33:01.530 --> 00:33:05.220
because we were putting
this kind of line on it.

00:33:05.220 --> 00:33:06.720
So we modulated carrier.

00:33:06.720 --> 00:33:12.330
Cos omega cy was the carrier
by the phase of Fourier.

00:33:12.330 --> 00:33:15.560
So we bumped the
lines up and down.

00:33:15.560 --> 00:33:17.280
We being, Stan.

00:33:17.280 --> 00:33:20.280
Stan bumped the lines up
and down in proportion

00:33:20.280 --> 00:33:23.450
to the brightness of Fourier.

00:33:23.450 --> 00:33:30.110
And that put Fourier's
content centered on omega c.

00:33:30.110 --> 00:33:34.890
It was hard to see from the
audience because your eyes--

00:33:34.890 --> 00:33:36.590
the projector projected omega c.

00:33:36.590 --> 00:33:38.840
It's hard for you to
see from the audience

00:33:38.840 --> 00:33:46.910
because your visible frequencies
in space don't go that high,

00:33:46.910 --> 00:33:50.510
but you beat it with
the stripey pattern,

00:33:50.510 --> 00:33:54.140
that modulates in space just
the way it modulates in time.

00:33:54.140 --> 00:33:55.940
And it takes a copy
of Fourier, which

00:33:55.940 --> 00:33:58.040
had been modulated up
to omega c and bumps it

00:33:58.040 --> 00:33:59.807
back down to the visible.

00:33:59.807 --> 00:34:00.890
That's why you can see it.

00:34:05.340 --> 00:34:07.090
Well, we're going to
see that in a moment.

00:34:07.090 --> 00:34:07.840
Good question.

00:34:10.900 --> 00:34:16.980
The idea is precisely the same
as the superheterodyne radio.

00:34:16.980 --> 00:34:18.510
If this is the
complicated picture

00:34:18.510 --> 00:34:20.010
that we would like
to look at-- this

00:34:20.010 --> 00:34:21.780
is the Fourier transform
or the complicated picture

00:34:21.780 --> 00:34:23.100
that we would like to look at.

00:34:23.100 --> 00:34:26.969
If we demodulate with
this stripe at omega c,

00:34:26.969 --> 00:34:32.460
we're able to bounce
down this pe house

00:34:32.460 --> 00:34:35.880
and we're able to see
that part of the picture,

00:34:35.880 --> 00:34:38.460
even though those frequencies
are too high for them

00:34:38.460 --> 00:34:40.156
to go through the microscope.

00:34:40.156 --> 00:34:41.989
There's a limited number
of frequencies that

00:34:41.989 --> 00:34:43.500
will go through the microscope.

00:34:43.500 --> 00:34:44.960
Just like there's a limited
number of frequencies

00:34:44.960 --> 00:34:46.440
that'll go through your eye.

00:34:46.440 --> 00:34:49.080
And we can take a band of
frequencies, that don't make it

00:34:49.080 --> 00:34:52.830
through the microscope, beat
it with this stripey pattern

00:34:52.830 --> 00:34:57.150
into a frequency range that
does go through the microscope.

00:34:57.150 --> 00:35:01.170
Then we can change
the stripey pattern.

00:35:01.170 --> 00:35:03.900
If we make stripey pattern
with slightly higher frequency,

00:35:03.900 --> 00:35:08.770
we get a different part
of the invisible spectrum.

00:35:08.770 --> 00:35:10.720
And we just keep repeating.

00:35:10.720 --> 00:35:13.420
There's a bit of an issue
that it's a 2D transform.

00:35:13.420 --> 00:35:14.860
We have to worry
about frequencies

00:35:14.860 --> 00:35:18.700
in x and frequencies in
y, but we are all experts

00:35:18.700 --> 00:35:19.720
at this sort of thing.

00:35:19.720 --> 00:35:22.930
The difference between stripes
this way and stripes this way

00:35:22.930 --> 00:35:26.080
is Fourier's this way
and Fourier's that way.

00:35:26.080 --> 00:35:27.670
You rotate the stripe.

00:35:27.670 --> 00:35:29.685
It just rotates the
Fourier transform.

00:35:33.400 --> 00:35:38.050
We can think about, in space
we can modulate like that

00:35:38.050 --> 00:35:41.630
or we can modulate like that.

00:35:41.630 --> 00:35:44.420
And in fact, what
we would like to do

00:35:44.420 --> 00:35:48.980
is modulate by a whole
bunch, so that we could

00:35:48.980 --> 00:35:50.480
take all these little regions--

00:35:50.480 --> 00:35:53.829
so say the circle
corresponds to the radius

00:35:53.829 --> 00:35:56.120
of frequencies that get
through the optical microscope.

00:35:56.120 --> 00:35:58.036
What we'd like to do is
put that little radius

00:35:58.036 --> 00:36:02.460
at every possible
place, one of the time,

00:36:02.460 --> 00:36:07.485
to bring down those frequencies
in the target, one at a time.

00:36:10.320 --> 00:36:11.580
So the idea--

00:36:11.580 --> 00:36:13.380
Then the problem
becomes, how do you

00:36:13.380 --> 00:36:16.340
make so many stripey patterns?

00:36:16.340 --> 00:36:20.600
And you have to generate
those stripey patterns at very

00:36:20.600 --> 00:36:22.280
high spatial frequencies.

00:36:22.280 --> 00:36:25.010
Very small distances.

00:36:25.010 --> 00:36:28.520
If you're going to
beat a microscope--

00:36:28.520 --> 00:36:30.320
Optical microscope
resolutions are

00:36:30.320 --> 00:36:32.900
on the order of 500 nanometers.

00:36:32.900 --> 00:36:34.710
Wavelength of light.

00:36:34.710 --> 00:36:37.640
So you're going to have to make
these patterns small compared

00:36:37.640 --> 00:36:40.170
to the wavelength of light.

00:36:40.170 --> 00:36:43.010
So Michael's idea
was interference.

00:36:43.010 --> 00:36:47.350
You take two coherent
laser beams, point them

00:36:47.350 --> 00:36:50.790
toward each other but
at a slight angle,

00:36:50.790 --> 00:36:55.050
and they will interfere
and make a stripey pattern.

00:36:55.050 --> 00:36:58.230
Then you turn on a
different pair of beams

00:36:58.230 --> 00:37:01.770
and you get a different
stripey pattern.

00:37:01.770 --> 00:37:02.598
Different.

00:37:02.598 --> 00:37:03.426
Different.

00:37:03.426 --> 00:37:04.050
Different.

00:37:04.050 --> 00:37:06.720
I'm showing on the left, the
spatial, and on the right,

00:37:06.720 --> 00:37:08.900
the Fourier transform.

00:37:08.900 --> 00:37:12.770
Fourier transform for
the stripey pattern.

00:37:12.770 --> 00:37:16.850
All light-- all pictures
have some dc because there's

00:37:16.850 --> 00:37:19.630
no negative photons.

00:37:19.630 --> 00:37:21.100
So that's this.

00:37:21.100 --> 00:37:23.980
And these are coding--

00:37:23.980 --> 00:37:28.210
the angle is coding
the orientation

00:37:28.210 --> 00:37:30.090
and the distance is
coding the pitch.

00:37:33.090 --> 00:37:34.230
Different stripey pattern.

00:37:34.230 --> 00:37:34.665
Different.

00:37:34.665 --> 00:37:35.165
Different.

00:37:35.165 --> 00:37:36.800
Different.

00:37:36.800 --> 00:37:38.524
There's a bunch of them.

00:37:48.490 --> 00:37:52.090
With 15 beams, you get 15k 2.

00:37:52.090 --> 00:37:54.540
Order 15 squared.

00:37:54.540 --> 00:37:56.950
That's the idea.

00:37:56.950 --> 00:37:58.270
And that was Michael.

00:37:58.270 --> 00:37:59.410
This is Stan.

00:37:59.410 --> 00:38:04.060
Stan figured out a way
to build an apparatus

00:38:04.060 --> 00:38:09.070
to take the beam from a
laser, break it into 15 parts,

00:38:09.070 --> 00:38:11.729
steer it with a
bunch of mirrors,

00:38:11.729 --> 00:38:13.270
and point them all
toward the center.

00:38:13.270 --> 00:38:17.190
So the target-- so the
lasers coming in over here.

00:38:17.190 --> 00:38:20.330
There's these pick-off mirrors
steering things around.

00:38:20.330 --> 00:38:23.790
This was some complicated
optimization that Stan did.

00:38:23.790 --> 00:38:27.060
Here is the region
of interest, which

00:38:27.060 --> 00:38:29.970
is this big on his microscope.

00:38:29.970 --> 00:38:33.870
And about 2 centimeters
down, the beams

00:38:33.870 --> 00:38:36.090
converge on a specimen.

00:38:36.090 --> 00:38:38.307
Which is right there.

00:38:38.307 --> 00:38:40.640
So if we zoom in and you can
see it a little bit better,

00:38:40.640 --> 00:38:43.830
there is a conventional
microscope objective

00:38:43.830 --> 00:38:46.140
with 15 beams fired toward it.

00:38:46.140 --> 00:38:49.770
Now the idea is you put the
specimen between the beams

00:38:49.770 --> 00:38:51.200
and the objective.

00:38:51.200 --> 00:38:55.650
And then you view the
stripey illuminated target

00:38:55.650 --> 00:38:58.770
with the microscope objective.

00:38:58.770 --> 00:39:02.010
Here is a picture
taken by Jay, where

00:39:02.010 --> 00:39:05.070
he took a bunch of small beads.

00:39:05.070 --> 00:39:09.690
It's easy to get plastic beads
of very uniform dimension.

00:39:09.690 --> 00:39:13.340
So these are about
1 micron beads

00:39:13.340 --> 00:39:15.240
and about a gazillion of them.

00:39:15.240 --> 00:39:18.090
So he just made a
solution of beads,

00:39:18.090 --> 00:39:20.730
put them on a glass
slide, evaporated it

00:39:20.730 --> 00:39:25.620
so that he would have a random
constellation of plastic beads

00:39:25.620 --> 00:39:27.930
all one micron in diameter.

00:39:27.930 --> 00:39:29.730
And here's one picture of it.

00:39:29.730 --> 00:39:31.740
And you can see the pixels.

00:39:31.740 --> 00:39:34.740
Each one of these squares
is one pixel in the camera.

00:39:34.740 --> 00:39:37.309
I'm zooming in a lot.

00:39:37.309 --> 00:39:38.850
Keep in mind that
these guys are only

00:39:38.850 --> 00:39:42.070
about a micron in dimension.

00:39:42.070 --> 00:39:45.490
But then if you change
the stripey pattern,

00:39:45.490 --> 00:39:48.570
you get a slightly
different picture.

00:39:48.570 --> 00:39:51.170
And if you change this
stripey pattern again.

00:39:51.170 --> 00:39:52.620
And again.

00:39:52.620 --> 00:39:53.120
And again.

00:39:53.120 --> 00:39:53.550
And again.

00:39:53.550 --> 00:39:54.050
And again.

00:39:54.050 --> 00:39:54.700
And again.

00:39:54.700 --> 00:39:59.510
So he recorded then, 300
and some odd pictures

00:39:59.510 --> 00:40:01.920
of the same thing with
different stripey patterns.

00:40:04.750 --> 00:40:07.690
Then he did some
signal processing

00:40:07.690 --> 00:40:11.030
and turned that sequence of
pictures into that picture.

00:40:14.380 --> 00:40:16.510
So you can see the
resolution is up a bit.

00:40:16.510 --> 00:40:20.560
The resolution is
very sub-pixel.

00:40:20.560 --> 00:40:23.020
You can see many
resolution elements

00:40:23.020 --> 00:40:27.050
inside one pixel from
the original picture.

00:40:27.050 --> 00:40:29.800
In fact, if you
compare the original

00:40:29.800 --> 00:40:32.260
to the reconstruction--

00:40:32.260 --> 00:40:37.840
so this is one picture taken
with uniform illumination.

00:40:37.840 --> 00:40:42.580
This is the result of
calculating some 300 pictures

00:40:42.580 --> 00:40:45.010
with structured illumination,
with different structure

00:40:45.010 --> 00:40:46.630
in each picture.

00:40:46.630 --> 00:40:49.190
And you can see a lot
better resolution here.

00:40:49.190 --> 00:40:50.800
In fact, you can
see here there's

00:40:50.800 --> 00:40:53.320
something that looks
like it might be a bead,

00:40:53.320 --> 00:40:57.800
but over here you can see more
clearly it's really two beads.

00:40:57.800 --> 00:41:01.430
And if you take a solitary
bead and plot the brightness

00:41:01.430 --> 00:41:03.260
through a line, you get this.

00:41:03.260 --> 00:41:05.630
But if you plot the brightness
through a reconstruction,

00:41:05.630 --> 00:41:07.475
you get something much narrower.

00:41:10.200 --> 00:41:16.590
Stan then developed a method
for scanning this around.

00:41:16.590 --> 00:41:19.590
He also developed a method
for measuring the point spread

00:41:19.590 --> 00:41:21.037
function directly.

00:41:21.037 --> 00:41:22.620
Here I want to show
you a measurement,

00:41:22.620 --> 00:41:25.590
same sort of apparatus,
with a 200 nanometer bead.

00:41:25.590 --> 00:41:27.752
A much smaller bead.

00:41:27.752 --> 00:41:29.460
Keep in mind that the
apparent brightness

00:41:29.460 --> 00:41:31.920
goes as the cube of diameter.

00:41:31.920 --> 00:41:34.230
So changing the diameter
by a factor of five,

00:41:34.230 --> 00:41:39.520
changed the apparent
brightness by 5 cubed.

00:41:39.520 --> 00:41:45.320
So here is a picture taken
with Stan's microscope.

00:41:45.320 --> 00:41:49.450
And if we take a row of pixels
and plot the brightness,

00:41:49.450 --> 00:41:52.300
this is the reconstructed
image by using

00:41:52.300 --> 00:41:55.330
standing wave illumination,
which is what we called it.

00:41:55.330 --> 00:41:58.900
And it's got an apparent
diameter of 290.

00:41:58.900 --> 00:42:02.320
The 290 is bigger than the
200 because of the blurring

00:42:02.320 --> 00:42:04.600
of the microscope.

00:42:04.600 --> 00:42:09.250
The prediction, based on the
angle of the laser beams--

00:42:09.250 --> 00:42:10.720
the resolution of
this microscope

00:42:10.720 --> 00:42:12.130
depends on the
angle of the laser

00:42:12.130 --> 00:42:14.620
beams because the angle
of the laser beams

00:42:14.620 --> 00:42:16.780
determines the
pitch of the fringe.

00:42:16.780 --> 00:42:21.010
That the pitch of
the stripey pattern.

00:42:21.010 --> 00:42:25.690
So the prediction, based
on the angle of the beams

00:42:25.690 --> 00:42:30.870
from the apparatus, was that
it should have been 250.

00:42:30.870 --> 00:42:32.700
And the fairest thing
to compare that to

00:42:32.700 --> 00:42:35.430
is, what would it have been
if we hadn't used any wave

00:42:35.430 --> 00:42:36.990
illumination?

00:42:36.990 --> 00:42:38.490
If we hadn't used
any illumination,

00:42:38.490 --> 00:42:42.490
it would have been
1500 nanometers.

00:42:42.490 --> 00:42:44.400
So you can see, there's
an enormous increase

00:42:44.400 --> 00:42:48.310
in the resolution by using this
phase modulated microscopy.

00:42:48.310 --> 00:42:51.240
So the point is that you
can use modulation for a lot

00:42:51.240 --> 00:42:53.121
other things than
communications.

00:42:53.121 --> 00:42:54.870
Because the application
and communications

00:42:54.870 --> 00:42:56.880
is terribly important,
but here was

00:42:56.880 --> 00:42:59.280
a completely different
application of modulation

00:42:59.280 --> 00:43:00.693
to improve microscopy.

00:43:03.870 --> 00:43:04.830
Thank you.

